WEBVTT

00:16.960 --> 00:17.460
XVII.

00:17.780 --> 00:23.520
A week passed, and no news arrived of Mr. Rochester. Ten days, and still he did not

00:23.520 --> 00:28.900
come. Mrs. Fairfax said she should not be surprised if he were to go straight from the

00:28.900 --> 00:33.820
East to London, and thence to the Continent, and not show his face again at Thornfield

00:33.820 --> 00:38.880
for a year to come. He had not infrequently quitted it in a manner quite as abrupt and

00:38.880 --> 00:44.620
unexpected. When I heard this, I was beginning to feel a strange chill and failing at the

00:44.620 --> 00:49.940
heart. I was actually permitting myself to experience a sickening sense of disappointment,

00:50.440 --> 00:55.580
but rallying my wits, and recollecting my principles, I at once called my sensations

00:55.580 --> 01:00.440
to order. And it was wonderful how I got over the temporary blunder, how I cleared

01:00.440 --> 01:05.440
up the mistake of supposing Mr. Rochester's movements, a matter in which I had any cause

01:05.440 --> 01:10.720
to take a vital interest. Not that I humbled myself by a slavish notion of inferiority.

01:11.060 --> 01:16.820
On the contrary, I just said, You have nothing to do with the master of Thornfield, further

01:16.820 --> 01:21.240
than to receive the salary he gives you for teaching his protégé, and to be grateful

01:21.240 --> 01:28.200
and kind treatment, as, if you do your duty, you have a right to expect at his hands. Be

01:28.200 --> 01:33.700
sure that is the only tie he seriously acknowledges between you and him, so don't make him the

01:33.700 --> 01:38.860
object of your fine feelings, your raptures, agonies, and so forth. He is not of your order.

01:39.240 --> 01:44.480
Keep to your caste, and be too self-respecting to lavish the love of the whole heart, soul,

01:44.520 --> 01:48.740
and strength where such a gift is not wanted, and would be despised.

01:49.500 --> 01:55.420
I went on with my day's business tranquilly, but ever and anon vague suggestions kept wandering

01:55.420 --> 02:01.700
across my brain of reasons why I should quit Thornfield, and I kept involuntarily framing

02:01.700 --> 02:07.000
advertisements and pondering conjectures about new situations. These thoughts I did not think

02:07.000 --> 02:09.940
to check. They might germinate and bear fruit if they could.

02:11.120 --> 02:15.600
Mr. Rochester had been absent upwards of a fortnight when the Post brought Mrs. Fairfax

02:15.600 --> 02:15.980
a letter.

02:16.620 --> 02:21.400
"'It is from the Master,' said she, as she looked at the direction. Now I suppose we

02:21.400 --> 02:26.280
shall know whether we are to expect his return or not.' And while she broke the seal and

02:26.280 --> 02:31.680
perused the document, I went on taking my coffee. We were at breakfast. It was hot,

02:31.980 --> 02:37.740
and I attributed to that circumstance a fiery glow which suddenly rose to my face. Why my

02:37.740 --> 02:43.140
hand shook, and why I involuntarily spilt half the contents of my cup into my saucer,

02:43.140 --> 02:44.780
I did not choose to consider.'

02:45.480 --> 02:50.380
"'Well, I sometimes think we are too quiet. But we run a chance of being busy enough now,

02:50.620 --> 02:55.720
for a little while at least,' said Mrs. Fairfax, still holding the note before her spectacles.

02:56.440 --> 03:01.980
"'Ere I permitted myself to request an explanation, I tied the string of Adele's pinafore, which

03:01.980 --> 03:06.720
happened to be loose. Having helped her also to another bun, and refilled her mug with

03:07.100 --> 03:08.580
I said nonchalantly,

03:09.080 --> 03:12.980
"'Mr. Rochester is not likely to return soon, I suppose.'

03:12.980 --> 03:18.620
"'Indeed he is. In three days, he says. That will be next Thursday, and not alone either.

03:18.880 --> 03:23.760
I don't know how many of the fine people at the Lees are coming with him. He sends directions

03:23.760 --> 03:28.420
for all the best bedrooms to be prepared, and the library and drawing-rooms are to be

03:28.420 --> 03:33.340
cleaned out. I am to get more kitchen-hands from the George Inn at Milkoat, and from wherever

03:33.340 --> 03:37.680
else I can. And the ladies will bring their maids, and the gentlemen their valets. So

03:37.680 --> 03:39.460
we shall have a full house of it.'

03:39.460 --> 03:43.800
And Mrs. Fairfax swallowed her breakfast, and hastened away to commence operations.

03:44.420 --> 03:49.540
The three days were, as she had foretold, busy enough. I had thought all the rooms at

03:49.540 --> 03:54.980
Thornfield beautifully clean and well arranged, but it appears I was mistaken. Three women

03:54.980 --> 04:00.300
were got to help, and such scrubbing, such brushing, such washing of paint and beating

04:00.300 --> 04:05.180
of carpets, such taking down and putting up of pictures, such polishing of mirrors

04:05.180 --> 04:10.540
and lusters, such lighting of fires in bedrooms, such airing of sheets and feather beds on

04:10.540 --> 04:16.160
hearths, I never beheld either before or since. Adèle ran quite wild in the midst of it.

04:16.460 --> 04:20.900
The preparations for company and the prospect of their arrival seemed to throw her into

04:20.900 --> 04:26.520
ecstasies. She would have Sophie to look over all her toilettes, as she called frocks, to

04:26.520 --> 04:33.000
any that were passé, and to air and arrange the new. For herself, she did nothing but

04:33.000 --> 04:38.460
caper about in the front chambers, jump on and off of the bedsteads, and lie on the mattresses

04:38.460 --> 04:43.560
and piled up bolsters and pillows before the enormous fires roaring in the chimneys. From

04:43.560 --> 04:49.200
school duties she was exonerated. Mrs. Fairfax had pressed me into her service, and I was

04:49.200 --> 04:54.340
all day in the storeroom, helping or hindering her and the cook, learning to make custards

04:54.340 --> 04:58.680
and cheesecakes and French pastry, to truss game and garnish dessert dishes.

04:59.260 --> 05:04.820
The party were expected to arrive on Thursday afternoon, in time for dinner at six. During

05:04.820 --> 05:10.400
the intervening period I had no time to nurse chimeras, and I believe I was as active and

05:10.400 --> 05:16.280
gay as anybody Adèle accepted. Still, now and then I received a damping check to my

05:16.280 --> 05:21.260
cheerfulness, and was in spite of myself thrown back on the region of doubts and portents

05:21.260 --> 05:27.140
and dark conjectures. This was when I chanced to see the third-storey staircase door, which

05:27.140 --> 05:32.860
of late had always been kept locked, open slowly and give passage to the form of Grace

05:32.860 --> 05:38.620
Poole in prim cap, white apron, and handkerchief, when I watched her glide along the gallery,

05:38.880 --> 05:44.300
her quiet tread muffled in a list slipper, when I saw her look into the bustling, topsy-turvy

05:44.300 --> 05:48.980
bedrooms, just to say a word, perhaps, to the charwoman about the proper way to polish

05:48.980 --> 05:54.540
a grate, or clean a marble mantelpiece, or take stains from papered walls, and then pass

05:54.540 --> 05:59.960
on. She would thus descend to the kitchen once a day, eat her dinner, smoke a moderate

05:59.960 --> 06:04.820
pipe on the hearth, and go back, carrying her pot of porter with her, for her private

06:04.820 --> 06:10.560
solace in her own gloomy upper haunt. Only one hour in all the twenty-four did she pass

06:10.560 --> 06:15.580
with her fellow servants below. All the rest of her time was spent in some low-sealed oaken

06:15.580 --> 06:22.000
of the second storey. There she sat, and sewed, and probably laughed drearily to herself,

06:22.460 --> 06:28.300
as companionless as a prisoner in his dungeon. The strangest thing of all was that not a

06:28.300 --> 06:33.680
soul in the house except me noticed her habits, or seemed to marvel at them. No one discussed

06:33.680 --> 06:39.060
her position or her employment. No one pitied her solitude or isolation. I once, indeed,

06:39.220 --> 06:43.580
overheard part of a dialogue between Leah and one of the charwomen of which Grace formed

06:43.580 --> 06:48.680
the subject. Leah had been saying something I had not caught, and the charwomen remarked,

06:48.880 --> 06:50.880
"'She gets good wages, I guess.'

06:50.880 --> 06:55.400
"'Yes,' said Leah. "'I wish I had as good. Not that mine are to complain of. There's

06:55.400 --> 06:59.860
no stinginess at Thornfield, but they are not one fifth of the sum Mrs. Poole receives.

07:00.220 --> 07:05.080
And she is laying by. She goes every quarter to the bank at Millcote. I should not wonder,

07:05.200 --> 07:09.680
but she has saved enough to keep her independent if she liked to leave. But I suppose she's

07:09.680 --> 07:14.560
got used to the place, and then she's not forty yet, and strong and able for anything.

07:15.000 --> 07:17.460
It is too soon for her to give up business.'

07:17.460 --> 07:20.460
"'She is a good hand, I dare say,' said the charwoman.

07:21.080 --> 07:26.240
"'Ah, she understands what she has to do. Nobody better,' rejoined Leah significantly.

07:26.980 --> 07:31.840
"'And it is not every one could fill her shoes. Not for all the money she gets.'

07:31.840 --> 07:36.000
"'That it is not,' was the reply. I wonder whether the master—'

07:36.000 --> 07:40.720
The charwoman was going on, but here Leah turned and perceived me, and she instantly

07:40.720 --> 07:42.200
gave her companion a nudge.

07:42.940 --> 07:48.180
"'Doesn't she know?' I heard the woman whisper. Leah shook her head, and the conversation

07:48.180 --> 07:53.080
was of course dropped. All I had gathered from it amounted to this—that there was

07:53.080 --> 07:58.100
a mystery at Thornfield, and that from participation in that mystery I was purposely excluded.

07:59.260 --> 08:04.340
Thursday came. All work had been completed the previous evening. Carpets were laid down,

08:04.340 --> 08:10.060
bed-hangings festooned, radiant white counter-panes spread, toilet-tables arranged, furniture

08:10.060 --> 08:15.540
rubbed, flowers piled in vases. Both chambers and saloons looked as fresh and bright as

08:15.540 --> 08:20.100
hands could make them. The hall, too, was scoured, and the great carved clock, as well

08:20.100 --> 08:24.520
as the steps and banisters of the staircase, were polished to the brightness of glass.

08:24.880 --> 08:30.160
In the dining-room the sideboard flashed resplendent with plate. In the drawing-room and boudoir

08:30.160 --> 08:32.980
vases of exotics bloomed on all sides.

08:34.060 --> 08:39.780
Afternoon arrived. Mrs. Fairfax assumed her best black satin gown, her gloves, and her

08:39.780 --> 08:44.220
gold watch, for it was her part to receive the company, to conduct the ladies to their

08:44.220 --> 08:49.160
rooms, etc. Adèle, too, would be dressed, though I thought she had little chance of

08:49.160 --> 08:54.020
being introduced to the party, that day at least. However, to please her, I allowed Sophie

08:54.020 --> 08:59.560
to apparel her in one of her short full muslin frocks. For myself I had no need to make any

08:59.560 --> 09:04.820
I should not be called upon to quit my sanctum of the school-rooms, for a sanctum it was

09:04.820 --> 09:08.120
now become to me, a very pleasant refuge in time of trouble.

09:08.920 --> 09:13.980
It had been a mild, serene spring day, one of those days which, toward the end of March

09:13.980 --> 09:18.940
or the beginning of April, rise shining over the earth as heralds of summer. It was drawing

09:18.940 --> 09:23.640
to an end now, but the evening was even warm, and I sat at work in the school-room with

09:23.640 --> 09:24.460
the window open.

09:24.460 --> 09:30.540
It gets late, said Mrs. Fairfax, entering in rustling state. I am glad I ordered dinner

09:30.540 --> 09:36.480
an hour after the time Mr. Rochester mentioned, for it is past six now. I have sent John down

09:36.480 --> 09:40.960
to the gates to see if there is anything on the road. One can see a long way from thence

09:40.960 --> 09:42.140
in the direction of Millcote.

09:42.820 --> 09:43.860
She went to the window.

09:44.200 --> 09:47.900
Here he is, said she. Well, John, leaning out, any news?

09:48.420 --> 09:51.700
Their coming man was the answer. They'll be here in ten minutes.

09:52.380 --> 09:58.240
Adèle flew to the window. I followed, taking care to stand on one side, so that, screened

09:58.240 --> 10:01.080
by the curtain, I could see without being seen.

10:02.020 --> 10:07.060
The ten minutes John had given seemed very long, but at last wheels were heard. Four

10:07.060 --> 10:12.860
equestrians galloped up the drive, and after them came two open carriages. Fluttering veils

10:12.860 --> 10:18.000
and waving plumes filled the vehicles. Two of the cavaliers were young, dashing-looking

10:18.000 --> 10:24.420
The third was Mr. Rochester, on his black horse, Miss Ruhr, pilot bounding before him.

10:24.680 --> 10:29.700
At his side rode a lady, and he and she were the first of the party. Her purple riding

10:29.700 --> 10:34.760
habit almost swept the ground, her veil streamed long on the breeze, mingling with its transparent

10:34.760 --> 10:38.240
folds and gleaming through them, shone rich raven ringlets.

10:38.960 --> 10:44.240
Miss Ingram, exclaimed Mrs. Fairfax, and away she hurried to her post below.

10:45.140 --> 10:49.760
The cavalcade, following the sweep of the drive, quickly turned the angle of the house,

10:49.900 --> 10:54.800
and I lost sight of it. Adèle now petitioned to go down, but I took her on my knee and

10:54.800 --> 10:59.200
gave her to understand that she must not on any account think of venturing in sight of

10:59.200 --> 11:04.960
the ladies, either now or at any other time, unless expressly sent for, that Mr. Rochester

11:04.960 --> 11:11.160
would be very angry, etc. Some natural tears she shed on being told this, but as I began

11:11.160 --> 11:13.880
to look very grave, she consented at last to wipe them.

11:14.740 --> 11:20.000
A joyous stir was now audible in the hall. Gentleman's deep tones and ladies' silvery

11:20.000 --> 11:26.380
accents blend harmoniously together, and distinguishable above all, though not loud, was the sonorous

11:26.380 --> 11:31.620
voice of the master of Thornfield Hall, welcoming his fair and gallant guests under its roof.

11:32.220 --> 11:36.760
Then light steps ascended the stairs, and there was a tripping through the gallery,

11:36.760 --> 11:41.800
and soft cheerful laughs, and opening and closing doors, and for a time a hush.

11:42.880 --> 11:47.720
Elle est changeante de toilettes, said Adèle, who listening attentively had followed every

11:47.720 --> 11:49.800
movement, and she sighed.

11:50.020 --> 11:55.520
Chez maman, said she, quand il y avait du monde, je l'a sauvée partout, au salon et

11:55.520 --> 12:01.640
de la loose chambreuse. Souvent je regardais les femmes de chambre coffrées et habillées

12:01.640 --> 12:06.620
les dames, et c'était si amusant, comme celle-là on apprende.

12:06.620 --> 12:11.580
Don't you feel hungry, Adèle? Mais oui, mademoiselle, voire cinq ou six

12:11.580 --> 12:14.820
yeux, qu'en nous n'avons pas mange.

12:15.780 --> 12:20.080
Well now, while the ladies are in their rooms, I will venture down and get you something

12:20.080 --> 12:26.380
to eat. And issuing from my asylum, with precaution, I sought a back-stairs which conducted directly

12:26.380 --> 12:31.720
to the kitchen. All in that region was fire and commotion. The soup and fish were in

12:31.720 --> 12:36.580
the last stage of projection, and the cook hung over her crucibles in a frame of mind

12:36.580 --> 12:41.680
and body threatening spontaneous combustion. In the servants' hall, two coachmen and

12:41.680 --> 12:46.420
three gentleman's gentlemen stood or sat around the fire. The Abigail's, I suppose,

12:46.480 --> 12:50.900
were upstairs with their mistresses. The new servants, that had been hired from Milcote,

12:51.180 --> 12:52.540
were bustling about everywhere.

12:53.500 --> 12:58.600
Threading this chaos, I at last reached the larder. There I took possession of a cold

12:58.600 --> 13:04.100
chicken, a roll of bread, some tarts, a plate or two, and a knife and fork. With this booty

13:04.100 --> 13:09.200
I made a hasty retreat. I had regained the gallery, and was just shutting the back door

13:09.200 --> 13:13.640
behind me, when an accelerated hum warned me that the ladies were about to issue from

13:13.640 --> 13:18.360
their chambers. I could not proceed to the schoolroom without passing some of their doors,

13:18.360 --> 13:23.440
and running the risk of being surprised with my cargo of victualage, so I stood still at

13:23.440 --> 13:28.960
the end, which, being windowless, was dark, quite dark now, for the sun was set and twilight

13:28.960 --> 13:34.160
gathering. Presently the chambers gave up their fair tenants one after another. Each

13:34.160 --> 13:39.560
came out gaily and airily, with dress that gleamed lustrous through the dark. For a moment

13:39.560 --> 13:44.620
they stood grouped together at the other extremity of the gallery, conversing in a key of sweet

13:44.620 --> 13:49.900
subdued vivacity. They then descended down the staircase almost as noiselessly as a bright

13:49.900 --> 13:54.880
mist rolls down a hill. Their collective appearance had left on me an impression of high-born

13:54.880 --> 14:00.540
elegance, such as I had never before received. I found Adele peeping through the schoolroom

14:00.540 --> 14:01.980
door, which she held ajar.

14:02.360 --> 14:07.480
"'What beautiful ladies!' cried she in English. "'Oh, I wish I might go to them. Do you think

14:07.480 --> 14:10.780
Mr. Rochester will send for us by-and-by, after dinner?'

14:10.780 --> 14:15.600
"'No, indeed I don't. Mr. Rochester has something else to think about. Never mind

14:15.600 --> 14:19.860
the ladies to-night. Perhaps you will see them to-morrow. Here is your dinner.' She

14:19.860 --> 14:24.300
was really hungry, so the chicken and tarts served to divert her attention for a time.

14:24.700 --> 14:29.900
It was well I secured this forage, or both she, I, and Sophie, to whom I conveyed a share

14:29.900 --> 14:34.580
of our past, would have run a chance of getting no dinner at all. Every one downstairs was

14:34.580 --> 14:36.440
too much engaged to think of us.

14:37.160 --> 14:42.260
The dessert was not carried out until after nine, and at ten footmen were still running

14:42.260 --> 14:47.960
to-and-fro with trays and coffee-cups. I allowed Adele to sit up much later than usual, for

14:47.960 --> 14:52.340
she declared she could not possibly go to sleep while the doors kept opening and shutting

14:52.340 --> 14:58.220
below, and people bustling about. Besides, she added, a message might possibly come from

14:58.220 --> 15:02.460
Mr. Rochester when she was undressed. Et alors quel dommage!

15:03.080 --> 15:08.280
I told her stories as long as she would listen to them, and then for a change I took her

15:08.280 --> 15:13.920
out into the gallery. The hall lamp was now lit, and it amused her to look over the balustrade

15:13.920 --> 15:18.820
and watch the servants passing backwards and forwards. When the evening was far advanced,

15:19.180 --> 15:24.080
a sound of music issued from the drawing-room, whither the piano had been removed, Adele

15:24.080 --> 15:29.740
and I sat down on the top step of the stairs to listen. Presently a voice blent with the

15:29.740 --> 15:35.520
rich tones of the instrument. It was a lady who sang, and sweet her notes were. The solo

15:35.520 --> 15:40.960
over, a duet followed, and then a glee, a joyous conversational murmur filled up the

15:40.960 --> 15:47.560
intervals. I listened long. Suddenly I discovered that my ear was wholly intent on analyzing

15:47.560 --> 15:52.680
the mingled sounds, and trying to discriminate amidst the confusion of accents those of

15:52.680 --> 15:58.660
Mr. Rochester. And when it caught them, which it soon did, it found a further task in framing

15:58.660 --> 16:02.220
the tones rendered by distance inarticulate into words.

16:03.080 --> 16:08.220
The clock struck eleven. I looked at Adele, whose head leant against my shoulder. Her

16:08.220 --> 16:13.740
eyes were waxing heavy, so I took her up in my arms and carried her off to bed. It was

16:13.740 --> 16:16.480
near one before the gentlemen and ladies sought their chambers.

16:17.680 --> 16:22.640
The next day was as fine as its predecessor. It was devoted by the party to an excursion

16:22.640 --> 16:27.360
to some site in the neighborhood. They set out early in the forenoon, some on horseback,

16:27.360 --> 16:32.680
the rest in carriages. I witnessed both the departure and the return. Miss Ingram, as

16:32.680 --> 16:38.120
before, was the only lady equestrian, and as before, Mr. Rochester galloped at her side.

16:38.540 --> 16:44.080
The two rode a little apart from the rest. I pointed out this circumstance to Mrs. Fairfax,

16:44.240 --> 16:46.180
who was standing at the window with me.

16:46.600 --> 16:50.500
"'You said it was not likely they should think of being married,' said I. But you

16:50.500 --> 16:54.860
see Mr. Rochester evidently prefers her to any of the other ladies.'

16:54.860 --> 16:57.360
"'Yes,' I dare say. No doubt he admires her.'

16:58.140 --> 17:03.040
"'And she him?' I added. Look how she leans her head towards him, as if she were conversing

17:03.040 --> 17:08.540
confidentially. I wish I could see her face. I have never had a glimpse of it yet.'

17:08.540 --> 17:13.120
"'You will see her this evening,' answered Mrs. Fairfax. I happened to remark to Mr.

17:13.340 --> 17:18.160
Rochester how much Adele wished to be introduced to the ladies, and he said, "'Oh, let her

17:18.160 --> 17:22.000
come into the drawing-room after dinner, and request Miss Eyre to accompany her.'

17:23.040 --> 17:27.560
"'Yes, he said that from mere politeness. I need not go, I am sure,' I answered.

17:28.360 --> 17:32.800
"'Well, I observed to him that as you were unused to company, I did not think you would

17:32.800 --> 17:37.720
like appearing before so gay a party, all strangers, and he replied in his quick way,

17:37.900 --> 17:43.000
"'Nonsense! If she objects, tell her it is my particular wish, and if she resists, say

17:43.000 --> 17:45.660
I shall come and fetch her in case of contumency.'

17:45.660 --> 17:51.000
"'I will not give him that trouble,' I answered. I will go, if no better may be. But I don't

17:51.000 --> 17:53.700
like it. Shall you be there, Mrs. Fairfax?'

17:53.700 --> 17:58.760
"'No, I played it off, and he admitted my plea. I'll tell you how to manage, so as

17:58.760 --> 18:03.360
to avoid the embarrassment of making a formal entrance, which is the most disagreeable part

18:03.360 --> 18:08.400
of the business. You must go into the drawing-room while it is empty, before the ladies leave

18:08.400 --> 18:13.100
the dinner-table. Choose your seat in any quiet nook you like. You need not stay long

18:13.100 --> 18:18.260
after the gentlemen come in, unless you please. Just let Mr. Rochester see you are there,

18:18.260 --> 18:23.680
and then slip away. No one will notice you. Will these people remain long, do you think?

18:24.400 --> 18:29.820
Perhaps two or three weeks. Certainly not more. After the Easter recess, Sir George

18:29.820 --> 18:34.520
Lynn, who was lately elected Member for Millcote, will have to go up to town and take his seat.

18:35.060 --> 18:40.500
I dare say Mr. Rochester will accompany him. It surprises me that he has already made so

18:40.500 --> 18:46.280
protracted a stay at Thornfield. It was with some trepidation that I perceived the hour

18:46.280 --> 18:51.620
when I was to repair with my charge to the drawing-room. Adèle had been in a state of

18:51.620 --> 18:56.260
ecstasy all day, after hearing she was to be presented to the ladies in the evening,

18:56.520 --> 19:01.820
and it was not till Sophie commenced the operation of dressing her that she sobered down. Then

19:01.820 --> 19:06.380
the importance of the process quickly steadied her, and by the time she had her curls arranged

19:06.380 --> 19:12.080
in well-smoothed drooping clusters, her pink satin frock put on, her long sash tied, and

19:12.080 --> 19:18.200
her lace mittens adjusted, she looked as grave as any judge. No need to warn her not to disarrange

19:18.200 --> 19:23.060
her attire. When she was dressed, she sat demurely down in her little chair, taking

19:23.060 --> 19:27.860
care previously to lift up the satin skirt, for fear she should crease it, and assured

19:27.860 --> 19:34.680
me she would not stir thence till I was ready. This I quickly was. My best dress, the silver-grey

19:34.680 --> 19:39.160
one, purchased for Miss Temple's wedding and never worn since, was soon put on, my

19:39.160 --> 19:44.380
hair was soon smoothed, my sole ornament, the pearl brooch, soon assumed. We descended.

19:45.660 --> 19:49.600
Fortunately there was another entrance to the drawing-room than that through the saloon

19:49.600 --> 19:54.740
where they were all seated at dinner. We found the apartment vacant, a large fire burning

19:54.740 --> 20:00.080
silently on the marble hearth, and wax candles shining in bright solitude, amid the exquisite

20:00.080 --> 20:04.500
flowers with which the tables were adorned. The crimson curtain hung before the arch,

20:04.500 --> 20:09.460
Slight as was the separation, this drapery formed from the party in the adjoining saloon.

20:09.700 --> 20:13.720
They spoke in so low a key that nothing of their conversation could be distinguished

20:13.720 --> 20:19.980
beyond a soothing murmur. Adele, who appeared still to be under the influence of a most

20:19.980 --> 20:24.560
solemnizing impression, sat down, without a word, on the footstool I pointed out for

20:24.560 --> 20:30.160
her. I retired to a window-seat, and taking a book from a table near, endeavoured to read.

20:30.900 --> 20:34.520
Adele brought her stool to my feet. Ere long she touched my knee.

20:35.060 --> 20:36.620
What is it, Adele?

20:37.280 --> 20:42.840
——Ece que je ne puis pas prendre une seule de ces fleurs magnifiques, mademoiselle,

20:43.340 --> 20:45.140
seulement pour compléter ma toilette.

20:46.260 --> 20:51.800
You think too much of your toilette, Adele, but you may have a flower. And I took a rose

20:51.800 --> 20:56.900
from a vase, and fastened it in her sash. She sighed a sigh of ineffable satisfaction,

20:56.900 --> 21:02.640
as if her cup of happiness were now full. I turned my face away. To conceal a smile

21:02.640 --> 21:06.940
I could not suppress, there was something ludicrous as well as painful in the little

21:06.940 --> 21:10.240
Parisian's earnest and innate devotion to matters of dress.

21:11.260 --> 21:16.260
A soft sound of rising now became audible. The curtain was swept back from the arch.

21:16.620 --> 21:20.800
Through it appeared the dining-room, with its lit luster pouring down light on the silver

21:20.800 --> 21:26.160
and glass of a magnificent dinner-service, covering a long table. A band of ladies stood

21:26.160 --> 21:31.820
in the opening. They entered, and the curtain fell behind them. There were but eight. Yet

21:31.820 --> 21:36.820
somehow as they flocked in, they gave the impression of a much larger number. Some of

21:36.820 --> 21:41.860
them were very tall, many of them were dressed in white, and all had a sweeping amplitude

21:41.860 --> 21:48.200
of a ray that seemed to magnify their persons as a mist magnifies the moon. I rose and curtsied

21:48.200 --> 21:53.160
to them. One or two bent their heads in return. The others only stared at me.

21:53.820 --> 21:58.740
They dispersed around the room, reminding me by the lightness and buoyancy of their

21:58.740 --> 22:04.460
movements of a flock of white plumey birds. Some of them threw themselves in half-reclining

22:04.460 --> 22:09.740
positions on the sofas and ottomans. Some bent over the tables, and examined the flowers

22:09.740 --> 22:15.340
and books. The rest gathered in a group around the fire. All talked in a low but clear tone

22:15.340 --> 22:20.040
which seemed habitual to them. I knew their names afterwards, and may as well mention

22:20.040 --> 22:20.640
them now.

22:21.580 --> 22:26.800
First, there was Mrs. Eshton, and two of her daughters. She had evidently been a handsome

22:26.800 --> 22:32.260
woman, and was well preserved still. Of her daughters, the eldest, Amy, was rather little,

22:32.780 --> 22:37.880
naïve and childlike in face and manner, and piquant in form. Her white muslin dress and

22:37.880 --> 22:44.380
blue sash became her well. The second, Louisa, was taller and more elegant in figure, with

22:44.380 --> 22:50.060
a very pretty face, of that order the French term me-noir chiffon. Both sisters were as

22:50.060 --> 22:56.120
fair as lilies. Lady Lynn was a large and stout personage of about forty, very erect,

22:56.440 --> 23:01.920
very haughty-looking, richly dressed in a satin robe of changeful sheen, her dark hair

23:01.920 --> 23:06.540
shewn glossily under the shade of an azure plume, and within the circlet of a band of

23:06.540 --> 23:06.940
gems.

23:08.040 --> 23:14.280
Mrs. Colonel Dent was less showy, but, I thought, more ladylike. She had a slight figure, a pale

23:14.630 --> 23:20.520
face, and fair hair. Her black satin dress, her scarf of rich foreign lace, and her pearl

23:20.520 --> 23:25.720
ornaments pleased me better than the rainbow radiance of the title Dame. But the three

23:25.720 --> 23:30.600
most distinguished, partly perhaps because the tallest figures of the band, were the

23:30.600 --> 23:36.680
dowager Lady Ingram, and her daughters, Blanche and Mary. They were all three of the loftiest

23:36.680 --> 23:42.200
stature of women. The dowager might be between forty and fifty, her shape was still fine,

23:42.200 --> 23:47.860
her hair, by candlelight at least, still black. Her teeth, too, were still apparently perfect.

23:48.380 --> 23:52.960
Most people would have termed her a splendid woman of her age, and so she was, no doubt,

23:53.140 --> 23:58.280
physically speaking. But then there was an expression of almost insupportable haughtiness

23:58.280 --> 24:03.420
in her bearing and countenance. She had Roman features, and a double chin, disappearing

24:03.420 --> 24:08.860
into a throat like a pillar. These features appeared to me not only inflated and darkened,

24:08.860 --> 24:14.800
but even furrowed with pride, and the chin was sustained by the same principle, in a

24:14.800 --> 24:21.520
position of almost preternatural erectness. She had likewise a fierce and hard eye. It

24:21.520 --> 24:26.280
reminded me of Mrs. Reade's. She mouthed her words in speaking. Her voice was deep,

24:26.580 --> 24:33.320
its inflections very pompous, very dogmatical, very intolerable in short. A crimson velvet

24:33.320 --> 24:39.720
and a shawl turban of some gold-rot Indian fabric invested her, I suppose she thought,

24:40.060 --> 24:42.040
with a truly imperial dignity.

24:43.720 --> 24:49.640
Blanche and Mary were of equal stature, straight and tall as poplars. Mary was too slim for

24:49.640 --> 24:55.080
her height, but Blanche was moulded like a dion. I regarded her, of course, with special

24:55.080 --> 25:00.200
interest. First, I wished to see whether her appearance accorded with Mrs. Fairfax's description.

25:00.200 --> 25:05.640
Secondly, whether it at all resembled the fancy miniature I had painted of her. And

25:05.640 --> 25:11.300
thirdly, it will out, whether it were such as I should fancy, likely to suit Mr. Rochester's

25:11.300 --> 25:18.080
tastes. As far as person went, she added point for point, both to my picture and to Mrs.

25:18.280 --> 25:23.240
Fairfax's description. The noble bust, the sloping shoulders, the graceful neck, the

25:23.240 --> 25:28.760
dark eyes and black ringlets, were all there. But her face—her face was like her mother's,

25:28.760 --> 25:34.420
a youthful, unfurrowed likeness, the same low brow, the same high features, the same

25:34.420 --> 25:40.360
pride. It was not, however, so Saturnine a pride. She laughed continually. Her laugh

25:40.360 --> 25:45.120
was satirical, and so was the habitual expression of her arched and haughty lip.

25:46.320 --> 25:51.420
Genius is said to be self-conscious. I cannot tell whether Miss Ingram was a genius, but

25:51.420 --> 25:57.600
she was self-conscious, remarkably self-conscious indeed. She entered into a discourse on botany

25:57.600 --> 26:02.540
with the gentle Mrs. Dent. It seemed Mrs. Dent had not studied that science, though,

26:02.580 --> 26:08.360
as she said, she liked flowers, especially wild ones. Miss Ingram had, and she ran over

26:08.360 --> 26:14.720
its vocabulary with an air. I presently perceived she was what is vernacularly termed trailing

26:14.720 --> 26:20.220
Mrs. Dent, that is, playing on her ignorance. Her trail might be clever, but it was decidedly

26:20.220 --> 26:26.200
not good-natured. She played, her execution was brilliant. She sang, her voice was fine.

26:26.540 --> 26:31.540
She talked French apart to her mamma, and she talked it well, with fluency and with

26:31.540 --> 26:36.020
a good accent. Mary had a milder and more open countenance

26:36.020 --> 26:41.600
than Blanche, softer features, too, and a skin some shades fairer. Miss Ingram was dark

26:41.600 --> 26:47.280
as a Spaniard. But Mary was deficient in life. Her face lacked expression, her eye luster.

26:47.680 --> 26:52.980
She had nothing to say, and having once taken her seat, remained fixed like a statue in

26:52.980 --> 26:56.420
its niche. The sisters were both attired in spotless white.

26:57.280 --> 27:02.140
And did I now think Miss Ingram such a choice as Mr. Rochester would be likely to make?

27:02.820 --> 27:08.160
I could not tell. I did not know his taste in female beauty. If he liked the majestic,

27:08.480 --> 27:13.760
she was the very type of majesty. Then she was accomplished, sprightly. Most gentlemen

27:13.760 --> 27:18.440
would admire her, I thought, and that he did admire her, I seem already to have obtained

27:18.440 --> 27:23.340
proof. To remove the last shade of doubt, it remained but to see them together.

27:24.860 --> 27:29.920
You are not to suppose, reader, that Adèle has all this time been sitting motionless

27:29.920 --> 27:35.740
on the stool at my feet. No, when the ladies entered, she rose, advanced to meet them,

27:36.040 --> 27:38.260
made a stately reverence, and said with gravity,

27:39.020 --> 27:40.060
Bonjour, mesdames.

27:40.940 --> 27:44.560
And Miss Ingram had looked down at her with a mocking air, and exclaimed,

27:44.560 --> 27:46.280
Oh, what a little puppet!

27:47.580 --> 27:49.060
Lady Lynne had remarked,

27:49.260 --> 27:53.900
It is Mr. Rochester's ward, I suppose, the little French girl he was speaking of.

27:54.820 --> 28:00.740
Mrs. Dent had kindly taken her hand, and given her a kiss. Amy and Louisa Eshton had cried

28:00.740 --> 28:03.600
out simultaneously, What a love of a child!

28:04.480 --> 28:09.820
And then they had called her to a sofa, where she now sat ensconced between them, chattering

28:10.360 --> 28:15.740
in French and broken English, absorbing not only the young lady's attention, but that

28:15.740 --> 28:19.860
of Mrs. Eshton and Lady Lynne, and getting spoiled to her heart's content.

28:20.740 --> 28:26.800
At last coffee is brought in, and the gentlemen are summoned. I sit in the shade, if any shade

28:26.800 --> 28:32.040
there be in this brilliantly lit apartment. The window-curtain half hides me. Again the

28:32.040 --> 28:37.120
arch yawns. They come. The collective appearance of the gentlemen, like that of the ladies,

28:37.120 --> 28:42.760
is very imposing. They are all costumed in black. Most of them are tall, some young.

28:43.380 --> 28:48.720
Henry and Frederick Lynne are very dashing sparks indeed, and Colonel Dent is a fine

28:48.720 --> 28:54.620
soldierly man. Mr. Eshton, the magistrate of the district, is gentleman-like. His hair

28:54.620 --> 28:59.420
is quite white, his eyebrows and whiskers still dark, which gives him something of the

28:59.420 --> 29:01.380
appearance of a noble father of the theatre.

29:02.320 --> 29:07.880
Lord Ingram, like his sisters, is very tall. Like them also he is handsome. But he shares

29:07.880 --> 29:12.960
Mary's apathetic and listless look. He seems to have more length of limb than vivacity

29:12.960 --> 29:14.860
of blood or vigour of brain.

29:15.540 --> 29:17.180
And where is Mr. Rochester?

29:18.080 --> 29:24.800
He comes in last. I am not looking at the arch, yet I see him enter. I try to concentrate

29:24.800 --> 29:30.000
my attention on the netting-needles, on the meshes of the purse I am forming. I wish only

29:30.000 --> 29:34.720
to think of the work I have in my hands, to see only the silver beads and silk threads

29:34.720 --> 29:40.500
that lie in my lap, whereas I distinctly behold his figure, and I inevitably recall the moment

29:40.500 --> 29:45.900
when I last saw it, just after I had rendered him what he deemed an essential service, and

29:45.900 --> 29:51.060
he, holding my hand and looking down in my face, surveyed me with eyes that revealed

29:51.060 --> 29:57.940
a heart full and eager to overflow, in whose emotions I had a part. How near had I approached

29:57.940 --> 30:03.860
him at that moment! What had occurred since, calculated to change his and my relative positions,

30:04.500 --> 30:10.500
yet now how distant, how far estranged we were! So far estranged that I did not expect

30:10.500 --> 30:15.800
him to come and speak to me. I did not wonder when, without looking at me, he took a seat

30:15.800 --> 30:19.720
at the other side of the room, and began conversing with some of the ladies.

30:22.340 --> 30:27.480
No sooner did I see that his attention was riveted on them, and that I might gaze without

30:27.480 --> 30:33.820
being observed, than my eyes were drawn involuntarily to his face. I could not keep their lids under

30:33.820 --> 30:37.640
control. They would rise, and the irises would fix on him.

30:38.320 --> 30:44.340
I looked, and had an acute pleasure in looking, a precious yet poignant pleasure, pure gold

30:44.340 --> 30:49.380
with a steely point of agony, a pleasure like what the thirst-perishing man might feel,

30:49.740 --> 30:54.440
who knows the well to which he has crept his poison, yet stoops and drinks divine draughts

30:54.440 --> 31:00.340
nevertheless. Most true is it that beauty is in the eye of the gazer. My master's colourless

31:00.340 --> 31:06.140
olive face, square massive brow, broad and jetty eyebrows, deep eyes, strong features,

31:06.340 --> 31:12.540
firm grim mouth, all energy, decision, will, were not beautiful, according to rule. Oh,

31:12.540 --> 31:17.240
but they were beautiful to me. They were full of an interest, an influence, that quite mastered

31:17.240 --> 31:21.460
me, that took my feelings from my own power, and fettered them in his.

31:22.400 --> 31:27.420
I had not intended to love him. The reader knows I had wrought hard to extirpate from

31:27.420 --> 31:32.160
my soul the germs of love there detected, and now, at the first renewed view of him,

31:32.400 --> 31:37.460
they spontaneously arrived, green and strong. He made me love him without looking at me.

31:38.160 --> 31:43.600
I compared him with his guests. What was the gallant grace of the lins, the languid elegance

31:43.600 --> 31:48.240
of Lord Ingram, even the military distinction of Colonel Dent, contrasted with his look

31:48.240 --> 31:54.140
of native pith and genuine power? I had no sympathy in their appearance, their expression,

31:54.620 --> 31:59.080
yet I could imagine that most observers would call them attractive, handsome, imposing,

31:59.540 --> 32:03.800
while they would pronounce Mr. Rochester at once harsh-featured and melancholy-looking.

32:04.440 --> 32:09.700
I saw them smile, laugh. It was nothing. The light of the candles had as much soul in it

32:09.700 --> 32:14.580
as their smile. The tinkle of the bell as much significance as their laugh. I saw Mr.

32:14.580 --> 32:20.160
Rochester smile. His stern features softened. His eye grew both brilliant and gentle, its

32:20.160 --> 32:26.100
ray both searching and sweet. He was talking, at the moment, to Louisa and Amy Eshton. I

32:26.100 --> 32:31.120
wondered to see them receive with calm that look which seemed to me so penetrating. I

32:31.120 --> 32:36.160
expected their eyes to fall, their colour to rise under it. Yet I was glad when I found

32:36.160 --> 32:41.400
that they were in no sense moved. He is not to them what he is to me, I thought. He is

32:41.400 --> 32:47.760
not of their kind. I believe he is of mine. I am sure he is. I feel akin to him. I understand

32:47.760 --> 32:52.760
the language of his countenance and movements. Though rank and wealth sever us widely, I

32:52.760 --> 32:57.340
have something in my brain and heart, in my blood and nerves, that assimilates me mentally

32:57.340 --> 33:02.660
to him. Did I say, a few days since, that I had nothing to do with him but to receive

33:02.660 --> 33:07.660
my salary at his hands? Did I forbid myself to think of him in any other light than as

33:07.660 --> 33:13.900
a paymaster? Blasphemy against nature! Every good, true, vigorous feeling I have gathers

33:13.900 --> 33:19.840
impulsively around him. I know I must conceal my sentiments. I must smother hope. I must

33:19.840 --> 33:25.340
remember that he cannot care much for me. For when I say that I am of his kind, I do

33:25.340 --> 33:30.600
not mean that I have his force to influence, and his spell to attract. I mean only that

33:30.600 --> 33:36.180
I have certain tastes and feelings in common with him. I must then repeat continually that

33:36.180 --> 33:41.140
we are forever sundered. And yet, while I breathe and think, I must love him.

33:42.520 --> 33:49.440
Coffee is handed. The ladies, since the gentlemen entered, have become lively as larks. Conversation

33:49.440 --> 33:55.580
waxes brisk and merry. Colonel Dent and Mrs. Eshton argue on politics. Their wives listen.

33:56.160 --> 34:01.380
The two proud dowagers, Lady Lynn and Lady Ingram, confabulate together. Sir George,

34:01.380 --> 34:06.500
whom by the by I have forgotten to describe, a very big and very fresh-looking country

34:06.500 --> 34:11.940
gentleman, stands before their sofa, coffee-cup in hand, and occasionally puts in a word.

34:12.620 --> 34:17.520
Mr. Frederick Lynn has taken a seat beside Mary Ingram, and is showing her the engravings

34:17.520 --> 34:23.680
of a splendid volume. She looks, smiles now and then, but apparently says little. The

34:23.680 --> 34:28.380
tall and phlegmatic Lord Ingram leans with folded arms on the chair-back of the little

34:28.380 --> 34:34.340
and lively Amy Eshton. She glances up at him, and chatters like a wren. She likes him better

34:34.340 --> 34:39.640
than she does Mr. Rochester. Henry Lynn has taken possession of an Ottoman at the feet

34:39.640 --> 34:44.880
of Louisa. Adele shares it with him. He is trying to talk French with her, and Louisa

34:44.880 --> 34:50.720
laughs at his blunders. With whom will blanching grim pair? She is standing alone at the table,

34:51.120 --> 34:56.460
bending gracefully over an album. She seems waiting to be sought. But she will not wait

34:56.460 --> 35:04.400
too long. She herself selects a mate. Mr. Rochester, having quitted the Eshton's, stands

35:04.400 --> 35:10.240
on the hearth as solitary as she stands by the table. She confronts him, taking her station

35:10.240 --> 35:12.320
on the opposite side of the mantelpiece.

35:12.960 --> 35:16.140
—Mr. Rochester, I thought you were not fond of children?

35:16.860 --> 35:17.880
—Nor am I.

35:18.400 --> 35:23.680
—Then what induced you to take charge of such a little doll as that?—pointing to

35:23.680 --> 35:25.580
Adele. Where did you pick her up?

35:26.320 --> 35:28.920
—I did not pick her up. She was left on my hands.

35:29.460 --> 35:31.160
—You should have sent her to school.

35:31.720 --> 35:34.680
—I could not afford it. Schools are so dear.

35:35.240 --> 35:40.060
—Why, I suppose you have a governess for her. I saw a person with her just now. Is

35:40.060 --> 35:45.300
she gone? Oh, no, there she is still, behind the window-curtain. You pay her, of course.

35:45.420 --> 35:50.440
I should think it quite as expensive. More so, for you have them both to keep in addition.

35:51.320 --> 35:57.260
I feared, or should I say I hoped, the illusion to me would make Mr. Rochester glance in my

35:57.260 --> 36:02.720
way, and I involuntarily shrank further into the shade. But he never turned his eyes.

36:03.260 --> 36:07.680
—I have not considered the subject, he said he indifferently, looking straight before

36:07.680 --> 36:13.420
him. No, you men never do consider economy and good sense. You should hear Mama on the

36:13.420 --> 36:18.860
chapter of governesses. Mary and I have had, I should think, a dozen at least in our day,

36:18.860 --> 36:25.840
half of them detestable and the rest ridiculous and all incubi. Were they not, Mama? Did you

36:25.840 --> 36:31.840
speak my own? The young lady, thus claimed as the dowager's special property, reiterated

36:31.840 --> 36:37.700
her question with an explanation. Oh, my dearest, don't mention governesses. The word makes

36:37.700 --> 36:43.340
me nervous. I have suffered a martyrdom from their incompetency and caprice. I thank Heaven

36:43.880 --> 36:51.740
Mrs. Dent here bent over to the pious lady and whispered something in her ear. I suppose

36:51.740 --> 36:56.520
from the answer elicited, it was a reminder that one of the anathematized race was present.

36:57.160 --> 37:00.580
—Tante P., said her ladyship, I hope it may do her good.

37:01.300 --> 37:07.260
Then, in a lower tone, but still loud enough for me to hear, I noticed her. I am a judge

37:07.260 --> 37:11.200
of physiognomy, and in hers I see all the faults of her class.

37:11.940 --> 37:15.360
—What are they, madam? inquired Mr. Rochester aloud.

37:15.720 --> 37:21.900
—I will tell you in your private ear, replied she, wagging her turban three times with portentous

37:21.900 --> 37:29.620
significancy. But my curiosity will be past its appetite. It craves food now. Ask Blanche.

37:29.700 --> 37:31.300
She is nearer you than I.

37:32.240 --> 37:38.100
—Oh, don't refer him to me, Mama. I have just one word to say of the whole tribe. They

37:38.100 --> 37:43.320
are a nuisance. Not that I ever suffered much from them. I took care to turn the tables.

37:43.760 --> 37:48.660
What tricks Theodore and I used to play on our Miss Wilsons and Miss Grays and Madame

37:48.660 --> 37:54.460
Joubert's! Mary was always too sleepy to join in a plot with spirit. The best fun was

37:54.460 --> 37:59.880
with Madame Joubert. Miss Wilson was a poor, sickly thing, lacrimose and low-spirited,

38:00.180 --> 38:08.080
not worth the trouble of vanquishing in short, and Mrs. Gray was coarse and insensible. No

38:08.080 --> 38:13.660
Madame Joubert. I see her yet in her raging passions, when we had driven her to extremities,

38:14.080 --> 38:19.020
spilt our tea, crumpled our bread and butter, tossed our books up to the ceiling, and played

38:19.020 --> 38:24.560
a cherry-vary with the ruler and desk, the fender and fire-irons. Theodore, do you remember

38:24.560 --> 38:25.600
those merry days?

38:26.780 --> 38:32.980
—Yes, to be sure I do, drawled Lord Ingram. And the poor old stick used to cry out, Oh,

38:32.980 --> 38:38.120
you villainous childs! And then we sermonised her on the presumption of attempting to teach

38:38.120 --> 38:42.060
such clever blades as we were, when she herself was so ignorant.

38:42.940 --> 38:49.680
We did. And Tito, you know I helped you in prosecuting, or persecuting, your tutor, way-faced

38:49.680 --> 38:55.160
Mr. Vining, the parson in the PIP, as we used to call him. He and Miss Wilson took the liberty

38:55.160 --> 39:00.400
of falling in love with each other, at least Tito and I thought so. We surprised sundry

39:01.020 --> 39:06.160
glances and sighs, which we interpreted as tokens of la belle passion. And I promised

39:06.160 --> 39:11.180
you the public soon had the benefit of our discovery. We employed it as a sort of lever

39:11.180 --> 39:15.740
to hoist our dead-weights from the house. Dear mamma there, as soon as she got an inkling

39:15.740 --> 39:20.720
of the business, found out that it was of an immoral tendency. Did you not, my lady

39:20.720 --> 39:21.180
mother?

39:21.960 --> 39:27.100
—Certainly my best. And I was quite right. Depend on that. There are a thousand reasons

39:27.100 --> 39:32.760
liaisons between governesses and tutors should never be tolerated a moment in any well-regulated

39:32.760 --> 39:39.840
houses. Firstly—Oh, gracious mammas, spare us the enumeration! All rest we all know them.

39:40.120 --> 39:44.840
Danger of bad example to the innocence of childhood, distractions and consequent neglect

39:44.840 --> 39:50.040
of duty on the part of the attached, mutual reliance and reliance, confidence thence resulting,

39:50.340 --> 39:55.280
insolence accompanying, mutiny and general blow-up. Am I right, Baroness Ingram of Ingram

39:55.280 --> 39:55.680
Park?

39:56.460 --> 39:59.260
—My lily-flower, you are right now as always.

40:00.100 --> 40:02.640
Then no more need be said. Change the subject.

40:03.820 --> 40:09.340
Amy Eshton, not hearing or not heeding this dictum, joined in with her soft infantine

40:09.340 --> 40:15.300
tone. Luisa and I used to quiz our governess too. But she was such a good creature. She

40:15.300 --> 40:20.060
would bear anything. Nothing put her out. She was never cross with us, was she, Luisa?

40:20.060 --> 40:26.280
No, never. We might do what we pleased, ransack her desk and her work-box, and turn her drawers

40:26.280 --> 40:31.040
inside out. And she was so good-natured, she would give us anything we asked for.

40:31.820 --> 40:37.060
I suppose now, said Miss Ingram, curling her lips sarcastically, we shall have an abstract

40:37.060 --> 40:42.500
of the memoirs of all the governesses extant. In order to avert such a visitation, I again

40:42.500 --> 40:47.020
move the introduction of a new topic. Mr. Rochester, do you second my motion?

40:47.880 --> 40:50.780
—Madam, I support you on this point, as on every other.

40:51.420 --> 40:56.540
Then on me be the onus of bringing it forward. Signor Eduardo, are you in voice to-night?

40:57.360 --> 41:04.080
Dona Bianca, if you command it, I will be. Then, Signor, I lay on you my sovereign behest,

41:04.280 --> 41:09.300
to furbish up your lungs and other vocal organs, as they will be wanted on my royal service.

41:10.320 --> 41:13.060
Who would not be the Rizio of so divine a Mary?

41:13.780 --> 41:19.000
—A fig for Rizio! cried she, tossing her head with all its curls, as she moved to the

41:19.000 --> 41:25.980
piano. It is my opinion the fiddler David must have been an insipid sort of fellow.

41:26.360 --> 41:31.380
I like Black Bothwell better. To my mind a man is nothing without a spice of the devil

41:31.380 --> 41:36.600
in him. And history may say what it will of James Hepburn. But I have a notion he was

41:36.600 --> 41:41.360
just the sort of wild, fierce bandit hero to whom I could have consented to gift my

41:41.360 --> 41:41.740
hand.

41:43.040 --> 41:48.100
—Gentlemen, you hear? Now which of you most resembles Bothwell? cried Mr. Rochester.

41:48.780 --> 41:52.020
—I should say the preference lies with you, responded Colonel Dent.

41:52.740 --> 41:56.080
—On my honour, I am much obliged to you, was the reply.

41:57.520 --> 42:02.500
Miss Ingram, who had now seated herself with a proud grace at the piano, spreading out

42:02.500 --> 42:09.180
her snowy robes in queenly amplitude, commenced a brilliant prelude, talking mean-time. She

42:09.180 --> 42:13.880
appeared to be on her high horse to-night. Both her words and her air seemed intended

42:13.880 --> 42:19.120
to excite not only the admiration, but the amazement of her auditors. She was evidently

42:19.120 --> 42:22.620
bent on striking them as something very dashing and daring indeed.

42:23.140 --> 42:28.160
"'Oh, I am so sick of the young men of the present day!' exclaimed she, rattling away

42:28.160 --> 42:34.380
at the instrument. Poor puny things! not fit to stir a step beyond papa's park gates,

42:34.380 --> 42:40.260
nor to go even so far without mamma's permission and guardianship. Creatures so absorbed in

42:40.260 --> 42:45.440
care about their pretty faces, and their white hands, and their small feet, as if a man had

42:45.440 --> 42:50.340
anything to do with beauty, as if loveliness were not the special prerogative of woman,

42:50.700 --> 42:56.120
her legitimate appanage and heritage. I grant an ugly woman is a blot on the fair face of

42:56.120 --> 43:01.640
creation. But as to gentlemen, let them be solicitous to possess only strength and valour.

43:01.640 --> 43:07.340
Let their motto be, Hunt, shoot, and fight, the rest is not worth a Philip. Such should

43:07.340 --> 43:09.080
be my device, were I a man.

43:09.940 --> 43:13.740
"'Whenever I marry,' she continued, after a pause which none interrupted,

43:14.120 --> 43:19.580
"'I am resolved my husband shall be not a rival, but a foil to me. I will suffer no

43:19.580 --> 43:25.040
competitor near the throne. I shall exact an undivided homage. His devotions shall not

43:25.040 --> 43:30.880
be shared between me and the shape he sees in his mirror. Mr. Rochester, now sing, and

43:30.880 --> 43:32.160
I will play for you.'

43:32.740 --> 43:35.160
"'I am all obedience,' was the response.

43:36.020 --> 43:41.520
"'Here, then, is a corsaire song. Know that I dote on corsaires, and for that reason sing

43:41.520 --> 43:47.400
it conspirito. Commands from Miss Ingram's lips would put spirit into a mug of milk and

43:47.400 --> 43:53.100
water. Take care, then. If you don't please me, I will shame you by showing you how things

43:53.100 --> 43:59.460
should be done. That is offering a premium on incapacity. I shall now endeavour to fail.

44:00.180 --> 44:05.840
"'Garde vous en bien. If you err willfully, I shall devise a proportionate punishment.'

44:05.840 --> 44:10.380
Miss Ingram ought to be clement, for she has it in her power to inflict a chastisement

44:10.380 --> 44:11.620
beyond mortal endurance.

44:12.260 --> 44:14.940
"'Ha! explain,' commanded the lady.

44:15.520 --> 44:20.760
"'Pardon me, madame. No need of explodation. Your own fine sense must inform you that one

44:20.760 --> 44:23.940
of your frowns would be a sufficient substitute for capital punishment.'

44:25.080 --> 44:30.760
"'Sing!' said she. And again touching the piano, she commenced an accompaniment in spirited

44:30.760 --> 44:31.280
style.

44:32.240 --> 44:37.520
"'Now is my time to slip away,' thought I. But the tones that then severed the air arrested

44:37.520 --> 44:44.420
me. Mrs. Fairfax had said Mr. Rochester possessed a fine voice. He did—a mellow, powerful

44:44.420 --> 44:49.860
bass into which he threw his own feeling, his own force, finding a way through the ear

44:49.860 --> 44:56.260
to the heart, and there waking sensation strangely. I waited till the last deep and full vibration

44:56.260 --> 45:01.860
had expired, till the tide of talk, checked an instant, had resumed its flow. I then quitted

45:01.860 --> 45:06.340
my sheltered corner, and made my exit by the side door, which was fortunately near.

45:07.140 --> 45:12.020
"'Thence a narrow passage led into the hall. In crossing it, I perceived my sandal was

45:12.020 --> 45:16.580
loose. I stepped to tie it, kneeling down for that purpose on the mat at the floor of

45:16.580 --> 45:22.780
the staircase. I heard the dining-room door unclose, a gentleman come out. Rising hastily,

45:22.860 --> 45:26.260
I stood face to face with him. It was Mr. Rochester.

45:27.660 --> 45:29.320
"'How do you do?' he asked.

45:29.860 --> 45:31.500
"'I am very well, sir.'

45:31.500 --> 45:34.620
"'Why did you not come and speak to me in the room?'

45:34.620 --> 45:39.460
"'I thought I might have retorted the question on him who put it, but I would not take that

45:39.460 --> 45:44.720
freedom. I answered, I did not wish to disturb you, as you seemed engaged, sir.'

45:45.340 --> 45:47.200
"'What have you been doing in my absence?'

45:48.120 --> 45:50.560
"'Nothing particular, teaching a dell as usual.'

45:51.440 --> 45:56.290
"'And getting a good deal paler than you were, as I saw at first sight. What is the matter?'

45:57.300 --> 45:58.390
"'Nothing at all, sir.'

45:59.000 --> 46:01.870
"'Did you take any cold that night you half-drowned me?'

46:02.580 --> 46:03.600
"'Not in the least.'

46:04.640 --> 46:07.380
"'Return to the drawing-room. You are deserting too early.'

46:07.920 --> 46:09.040
"'I am tired, sir.'

46:09.620 --> 46:11.320
He looked at me for a minute.

46:11.900 --> 46:14.860
"'And a little depressed, he said. What about? Tell me.'

46:15.720 --> 46:17.680
"'Nothing, nothing, sir. I am not depressed.'

46:18.380 --> 46:23.500
"'But I affirm that you are. So much depressed that a few more words would bring tears to your eyes.

46:23.840 --> 46:28.580
Indeed, they are there now, shining and swimming, and a bead has slipped from the lash and fallen

46:28.580 --> 46:34.800
on to the flag. If I had time, and was not in mortal dread of some prating prig of a servant

46:34.800 --> 46:40.180
passing, I would know what all this means. Well, to-night I excuse you. But understand that,

46:40.320 --> 46:45.040
so long as my visitors stay, I expect you to appear in the drawing-room every evening.

46:45.440 --> 46:50.800
It is my wish. Don't neglect it. Now go and send Sophie for a dell. Good night, my—'

46:51.360 --> 46:54.940
He stopped, bit his lip, and abruptly left me.

